commitResults.messageTitle: Implement Edit Command that supports Phone number lookups
commitResults.messageBody:
Edit Command: updates a Customer's details via index of Customer in underlying implementation of an ArrayList.

This is not practical to keep track in real life as the indexes are constantly changing, especially if we want to delete a Customer from bobaBot.

Identifying a Customer via his or her Phone number allows us to bypass this problem while ensuring the identifier is kept unique.

Let's use the Phone number to search for the underlying index instead of having the index provided at input.

Edit Command: can have multiple identifiers for Customers i.e. Email, Phone number

Edit Command only supports if Phone number is the identifier.

Providing multiple ways to identify a Customer's profile is more user-friendly because different Customers may opt for a different identifier.

Let's,
* update each prefix to be independent of the other prefixes
* add more identifiers for the Edit Command

commitResults.messageBody:
Edit command: make command only accept maximum of 1 edit per Customer field

Edit command now takes the first prefix of a field and ignores the rest of the inputs with the same prefix.

An Edit command that accepts only 1 edit per Customer field reduces the odds of the user accidentally making an unintentional edit.

Let's,
* add another block to prevent multiple of the same prefixes from being accepted by the command
* fix Increase and Decrease command in a similar fashion to be consistent with the above mentioned behavior

Add command: Immediately flag the "BDAY" Tag if current month is birthday month

Add command now does not immediately flag the "BDAY" Tag.

Let's,
* check the local month during execution of Add command to determine whether it is appropriate to flag the "BDAY" tag upon completion of command

commitResults.messageBody: Update "add" feature description
Update target user profile and value proposition.

AB3 adds a person to the addressbook, while bobaBot adds a customer to bobaBot. bobaBot also tracks different information about the customer.

Current AB3 version of Add feature does not fulfil bobaBot's requirements.

Let's update the information of customers being tracked and the Javadocs for the Add feature respectively.

More accurate description of the Javadocs help collaborating developers to understand bobaBot better.

isSamePerson method: make it check for phone number and email address.

isSamePerson method checks for same name to determine if 2 Customers are the same.

Different Customers can have the same name but are different people.

Let's make isSamePerson check for phone number and email address which are unique to each Customer.

Using unique identifiers instead is preferable because this allows 2 Customers to have same names but both to exist in bobaBot.

commitResults.messageTitle: Update AddCommand to only accept unique Prefixes
commitResults.messageBody:
AddCommand allows multiple prefixes for unique fields. (e.g. "`add n/name1 n/name2 ...`" will add a new Customer with name of "`name2`"). `name1` will not be read.

Allowing multiple entries for unique fields causes unintended outcomes.

Checking whether unique fields have unique entries will prevent unintended outcomes, such as `name1` not being read in the example above.

Let's perform this check in AddCommandParser.java since this class is responsible for dealing with user input.

commitResults.messageTitle: Update Person to include BirthdayMonth field
commitResults.messageBody:
Person has no BirthdayMonth field.

This is not the best representation of our customers. Customers have a birthday month and we can give them discounts during their birthday months.

Let's include BirthdayMonth field into the Person class, so that we can give birthday discounts to customers accordingly.

commitResults.messageBody:
The current DeleteCommand is executed using index person in the list.

This limits the ability of the cashier to delete/manage customers since
the implementation only supports index.

The new DeleteCommand is no longer executed via index but via 2 options:
* Phone Number or
* Email
The cashier can now delete the customers by specifying either the prefix for
phone number 'p/PHONE_NUMBER' or prefix for email 'e/EMAIL'.

This offers more flexibility in the fields the cashier can use to delete/manage
the customers.

commitResults.messageTitle: Update tests related to DeleteCommand and DeleteCommandParser
commitResults.messageBody:
The existing test cases for DeleteCommand and DeleteCommandParser
are testing based on deleting via index.

We adopted a new implementation of DeleteCommand to delete via
phone number or email input, hence we have to edit the test
cases according to the new implementation.

Let's remove the test cases related to testing via index and
create new test cases based on phone number and email inputs.

Some tests for valid inputs include:
* Valid phone number/email specified ("delete p/12345678")
or ("delete e/test@test.com")

Some tests for invalid inputs include:
* Multiple same prefixes ("delete p/12345678 p/87654321") or
("delete e/test@gmail.com e/test1@gmail.com") will not work
since there are multiple prefixes specified
* Validity of phone number/email input, whether there are
customers with corresponding email/phone number
* Multiple different prefixes
("delete p/12345678 e/test@gmail.com") will not work since
there are both phone number and email specified
* Empty inputs and prefixes such as ("delete"), ("delete p/"),
("delete e/") will not work
* Invalid formats like ("delete hello123") without prefix

This helps to cover some of the potential invalid inputs from
users.

There are also changes made to some of these methods:
* DeleteCommand's equals method
* DeletePersonDescriptor's equals method
* findNum method
* findEmail method
